I am seconded to the KNMI (Royal Netherlands Meteorological Institute) where I work with the L01B processor team on issues related to statistical issues related to the calibration of the instrument and data analysis algorithms.", 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Giuseppe', 'last_name': 'Vacanti', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Principal Scientist at cosine | measurement systems'}]}, {'title': 'Interplanetary Electron Model', 'date': {'start': {'month': 1, 'day': None, 'year': 2010}, 'end': {'month': 5, 'day': None, 'year': 2012}}, 'description': 'A new model of the radiation environment around Jupiter has been developed by cosine and the Surrey Space Centre (UK). The model, which accounts for the electron spectrum induced by that planet’s strong magnetic field, is being used by the European Space Agency, and other space agencies around the world, to study the safety of satellite instrumentation.

Space is a hostile environment not only for man, but also for the instruments aboard satellites. In particular, space instrumentation must be protected against the adverse effects of cosmic electrons and other charged particles, that can damage the sophisticated optical and electronic components that instruments are made of. In order to take adequate countermeasures it is important to know the intensity and energy distributions of the particles along the path followed by the satellite. To this end models have been developed, and are routinely used as input into the design of spacecraft shields.

The European Space Agency has collected many of the available models related to the space environment in the Space Environment Information System (SPENVIS). Through SPENVIS spacecraft engineers and scientists can estimate the amount of radiation that a satellite encounters when moving across the Solar System.

The new model developed by cosine and its UK partner has been included in SPENVIS since September 2011. It estimates the spatial, temporal, and spectral distribution of the electrons accelerated by the powerful Jovian magnetic field. Once accelerated these electrons move across the Solar System along the solar magnetic field lines, and are a weak but measurable component of the cosmic radiation across the heliosphere. The predictions of the model have been found to be in good agreement with the electron measurements carried out by spacecraft in orbit around the Earth.

The Jupiter model is part of a suite of tools developed to model the interplanetary electron spectrum, also developed by this team.', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Giuseppe', 'last_name': 'Vacanti', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Principal Scientist at cosine | measurement systems'}, {'type': 'nonStandardizedContributor', 'first_name': None, 'last_name': None, 'name': 'Erik Maddox', 'headline': None}, {'type': 'nonStandardizedContributor', 'first_name': None, 'last_name': None, 'name': 'Ben Taylor', 'headline': None}, {'type': 'nonStandardizedContributor', 'first_name': None, 'last_name': None, 'name': 'Craig Underwood', 'headline': None}]}, {'title': 'High Accuracy Matching of Planetary Images', 'date': {'start': {'month': 1, 'day': None, 'year': 2005}, 'end': {'month': 9, 'day': None, 'year': 2005}}, 'description': 'A study of how the displacement of features on the surface of a planet can be detected through pattern recognition algorithms.
